11
00:03:46,300 --> 00:03:53,039
in software engineering we start from a very messy situation

12
00:03:55,280 --> 00:04:14,610
in the real world we observe structured data behaviors and events yes bugs happen users complain

13
00:04:16,019 --> 00:04:26,319
systems slow down and teams react based on experience or intuition at the stage

14
00:04:27,600 --> 00:04:34,800
information exists but it is not organized and it's hard to reason about it

15
00:04:37,410 --> 00:04:51,699
to move forward we introduce a model a model acts as a bridge between reality and numbers

16
00:04:54,560 --> 00:04:54,879
it

17
00:04:54,879 --> 00:05:02,579
defines rules, abstractions and assumptions. Instead of dealing with raw

18
00:05:02,579 --> 00:05:12,180
observations, we decide what matters, what we want to measure and how different

19
00:05:12,180 --> 00:05:21,629
observations are related. Without this step, any number we produce would be

20
00:05:21,629 --> 00:05:32,410
arbitrary. Once the model is defined, we can assign numbers. These numbers are not

21
00:05:32,410 --> 00:05:42,240
random. They represent structures, metrics that follow the rules of the model. If

22
00:05:42,240 --> 00:05:52,920
the model is weak or unclear, the numbers will be misleading. If the model is sound,

23
00:05:52,920 --> 00:05:57,819
the numbers become meaningful and useful for

24
00:05:57,819 --> 00:06:09,899
analysis, prediction and decision-making. The key idea here is the transition from

25
00:06:09,899 --> 00:06:19,100
intuition to reward. Rather than relying on personal judgments or information

26
00:06:19,100 --> 00:06:27,870
opinions, software measurement aims to create objective, repeatable and

27
00:06:27,870 --> 00:06:32,009
defensible results. This is the foundation of the model.

28
00:06:32,009 --> 00:06:39,959
This is the foundation for valid metrics, reliable predictions and better engineering

29
00:06:39,959 --> 00:06:43,660
decisions later in the course.

