00:07:08,829 --> 00:07:11,230
The trap of native measurements.

33
00:07:11,230 --> 00:07:11,730
Yes.

34
00:07:11,730 --> 00:07:25,199
In software engineering, using numbers can feel safe and objective. However, numbers

35
00:07:25,199 --> 00:07:39,069
alone do not always give real understanding. A common example is Fouls per kilo. At first

36
00:07:39,069 --> 00:07:46,589
gallons, this metric looks simple and useful, but its meaning changes depending on what

37
00:07:46,589 --> 00:07:47,110
we are trying to say.

38
00:07:47,110 --> 00:07:56,160
The goals of the metric test are in the following categories.

39
00:07:56,160 --> 00:08:05,670
When the focus is on the testing process, Fouls per kilo can be helpful.

40
00:08:05,670 --> 00:08:15,850
In this case, the goal is to understand how often defects are discovered. A higher number

41
00:08:15,850 --> 00:08:25,269
may indicate active and effective testing. Here, the metric supports the attributes we care about,

42
00:08:25,269 --> 00:08:35,399
so it works well the situation changes when we look at tester efficiency comparing

43
00:08:37,399 --> 00:08:53,250
comparing two testers using false ignores program complexity one tester may work on a very complex

44
00:08:53,250 --> 00:09:03,700
system while the other works on a simple one the numbers may look comparable but the conclusion

45
00:09:03,700 --> 00:09:15,590
would be unfair in this context the metric give gives a wrong signal the biggest risk

46
00:09:15,590 --> 00:09:24,720
appears when faults per kilo is used for code quality a system with many detected faults

47
00:09:26,000 --> 00:09:26,720
may actually

48
00:09:26,799 --> 00:09:39,779
have better quality because it was tested more truly another system may show fever faults simply

49
00:09:39,779 --> 00:09:49,299
because the problems may look comparable but the conclusion would be unfair in this context

50
00:09:50,610 --> 00:10:04,899
the metric gives a wrong signal the biggest risk appears when faults is used for

51
00:10:05,059 --> 00:10:14,049
code quality a system with many detected faults may fault mean mistake right a system with yes

52
00:10:17,669 --> 00:10:26,929
a system with yes it's my with many detected false they may have maybe a better quality

53
00:10:26,929 --> 00:10:37,679
because it was tested more truly yes the system may have many faults but because of that best quality

54
00:10:38,639 --> 00:10:43,639
because it was tested more truly, it may be better.

55
00:10:45,809 --> 00:10:49,570
Another system may show fever faults

56
00:10:49,570 --> 00:10:54,570
simply because problems were not found yet.

57
00:10:54,909 --> 00:11:03,080
In this case, the metric can easily mislead decision makers.

58
00:11:03,080 --> 00:11:10,190
The main lesson is simple.

59
00:11:10,190 --> 00:11:15,190
Numbers do not automatically create insights.

60
00:11:15,190 --> 00:11:20,509
Before measuring, we must clearly define

61
00:11:20,509 --> 00:11:27,139
what entity we are studying

62
00:11:27,139 --> 00:11:32,139
and which attributes we want to understand.

63
00:11:32,139 --> 00:11:37,750
Only in this case, the metric can easily mislead decision makers.

64
00:11:37,750 --> 00:11:42,750
Only they can metric become meaningful

65
00:11:42,750 --> 00:11:45,750
and trustworthy.

66
00:11:45,750 --> 00:11:54,740
The next slide.

67
00:11:54,740 --> 00:12:01,669
I don't have mouse, so I'm encountering some difficulties

68
00:12:01,669 --> 00:12:07,080
to use that, unfortunately.

69
00:12:07,080 --> 00:12:09,750
How can I do that?

70
00:12:09,750 --> 00:12:12,750
Okay, here I think.

71
00:12:12,750 --> 00:12:16,549
Model is an abstract of reality.

72
00:12:16,549 --> 00:12:30,539
In measurements, we never work with reality exactly as it is.

73
00:12:30,539 --> 00:12:34,090
Instead, we create a model.

74
00:12:34,090 --> 00:12:40,789
A model helps us remove unnecessary detail

75
00:12:40,789 --> 00:12:46,370
and focus only on what matters for our goal.

76
00:12:46,370 --> 00:12:53,419
This makes complex things easier to understand and compare.

77
00:12:54,419 --> 00:13:01,340
Think about measuring a person's height.

78
00:13:01,340 --> 00:13:06,879
Small decisions change the results.

79
00:13:06,879 --> 00:13:11,490
Do we include shows or not?

80
00:13:11,490 --> 00:13:13,970
What about hair?

81
00:13:13,970 --> 00:13:19,899
Is the person standing straight or not?

82
00:13:19,899 --> 00:13:24,470
Each choice affects the final number.

83
00:13:24,470 --> 00:13:29,399
Before using the ruler,

84
00:13:29,399 --> 00:13:32,399
we must agree on these rules.

85
00:13:32,399 --> 00:13:38,500
Without them, the measurement has no clear meaning.

86
00:13:38,500 --> 00:13:41,980
The same idea applies to software,

87
00:13:41,980 --> 00:13:46,980
especially when we talk about lines of code,

88
00:13:46,980 --> 00:13:50,070
LOC, lines of code.

89
00:13:50,070 --> 00:13:53,070
Several questions appear immediately.

90
00:13:53,070 --> 00:13:56,970
Should commands be counted?

91
00:13:56,970 --> 00:14:01,700
Do data declarations matter?

92
00:14:01,700 --> 00:14:09,559
What if multiple statements are written on the same line?

93
00:14:09,559 --> 00:14:13,559
So, different answers lead to different numbers,

94
00:14:13,559 --> 00:14:17,070
even for the same program.

95
00:14:17,070 --> 00:14:21,070
This is why the model is important.

96
00:14:21,070 --> 00:14:26,480
The number itself is not the problem.

97
00:14:26,480 --> 00:14:29,480
The problem is using a number

98
00:14:29,480 --> 00:14:34,480
without clearly defining the model behind it.

99
00:14:35,480 --> 00:14:38,509
If the rules are unclear,

100
00:14:38,509 --> 00:14:42,960
comparisons become unreliable

101
00:14:42,960 --> 00:14:46,960
and conclusions become weak.

102
00:14:46,960 --> 00:14:50,470
So, the key idea is simple.

103
00:14:50,470 --> 00:14:54,460
Before measuring software,

104
00:14:54,460 --> 00:14:59,460
we must first decide what we include,

105
00:14:59,460 --> 00:15:02,460
what we ignore, and why.

106
00:15:02,460 --> 00:15:06,169
Only then can a metric represent reality.

107
00:15:06,169 --> 00:15:09,169
Even a metric represents reality

108
00:15:09,169 --> 00:15:13,169
in a useful and consistent way.

109
00:15:13,169 --> 00:15:36,590
So, let's skip the other slides.

110
00:15:36,590 --> 00:15:46,070
Imagine a dog that is very intelligent.

111
00:15:46,070 --> 00:15:51,419
We have a dog that is very intelligent.

112
00:15:51,419 --> 00:15:55,419
Let's assume that this dog understands people.

113
00:15:55,419 --> 00:15:59,159
It solves problems

114
00:15:59,159 --> 00:16:04,220
and reacts correctly in many situations.

115
00:16:04,220 --> 00:16:07,220
It's very clever.

116
00:16:07,220 --> 00:16:13,220
However, this dog cannot read or write.

117
00:16:13,220 --> 00:16:18,610
Now, think about giving this dog

118
00:16:18,610 --> 00:16:22,409
a written IQ test.

119
00:16:22,409 --> 00:16:24,409
We assume that we have given to the dog

120
00:16:24,409 --> 00:16:26,409
an IQ test.

121
00:16:26,409 --> 00:16:30,600
And the result will be what?

122
00:16:30,600 --> 00:16:32,600
The result will be zero.

123
00:16:32,600 --> 00:16:37,600
Even though the dog is clearly smart.

124
00:16:37,600 --> 00:16:42,779
This situation shows a serious measurement problem.

125
00:16:42,779 --> 00:16:48,860
The mistake is not in the dog.

126
00:16:48,860 --> 00:16:53,179
The mistake is in the measurement method.

127
00:16:53,179 --> 00:16:57,179
We focused only on the formal system.

128
00:16:57,179 --> 00:16:59,600
The tests,

129
00:16:59,600 --> 00:17:01,600
but clearly defining

130
00:17:01,600 --> 00:17:05,599
what we really wanted to measure in the world,

131
00:17:05,599 --> 00:17:07,599
which is intelligence.

132
00:17:07,599 --> 00:17:17,259
Here the empirical attribute is intelligence.

133
00:17:17,259 --> 00:17:21,420
But intelligence has many aspects.

134
00:17:21,420 --> 00:17:23,519
Problem solving,

135
00:17:23,519 --> 00:17:26,190
learning,

136
00:17:26,190 --> 00:17:29,190
adaptation and understanding.

137
00:17:29,190 --> 00:17:34,700
Writing ability is only one smart part.

138
00:17:34,700 --> 00:17:41,500
When the model ignores these other aspects,

139
00:17:41,500 --> 00:17:49,089
the number no longer represents reality.

140
00:17:49,089 --> 00:17:52,660
This leads to an important lesson

141
00:17:52,660 --> 00:18:01,299
for software measurements.

142
00:18:01,299 --> 00:18:04,299
If we jump directly to numbers

143
00:18:04,299 --> 00:18:08,299
without defining the attribute clearly,

144
00:18:08,299 --> 00:18:11,880
the results can be misleading.

145
00:18:11,880 --> 00:18:18,220
A valid measure needs a well-defined model

146
00:18:18,220 --> 00:18:22,220
that connects real-world characteristics

147
00:18:22,220 --> 00:18:25,220
to numbers in a meaningful way.

148
00:18:25,220 --> 00:18:44,079
So, the key message is simple.

149
00:18:44,079 --> 00:18:47,079
If the attribute is not clearly defined

150
00:18:47,079 --> 00:18:49,079
in the real world,

151
00:18:49,079 --> 00:18:52,430
any number we assign to it

152
00:18:52,430 --> 00:18:55,690
becomes meaningless,

153
00:18:55,690 --> 00:18:59,880
no matter how precise it looks.

154
00:18:59,880 --> 00:19:08,349
The next slide will be

155
00:19:08,349 --> 00:19:11,349
Illusion of Complexity.

156
00:19:11,349 --> 00:19:13,900
Let's look at here.

157
00:19:13,900 --> 00:19:35,119
In this study,

158
00:19:35,119 --> 00:19:39,119
we look at a very well-known software metric,

159
00:19:39,119 --> 00:19:44,390
McCabe's Psylomatic Number.

160
00:19:44,390 --> 00:19:48,390
It is shown as V .

161
00:19:48,390 --> 00:19:51,900
This metric is often used

162
00:19:51,900 --> 00:19:55,609
to talk about software complexity.

163
00:19:55,609 --> 00:19:57,609
The formula is basic

164
00:19:57,609 --> 00:19:59,609
and it is shown in two ways.

165
00:19:59,609 --> 00:20:02,930
First, V is equal to

166
00:20:02,930 --> 00:20:06,019
e minus n plus 2,

167
00:20:06,019 --> 00:20:09,019
where e means edges

168
00:20:09,019 --> 00:20:11,019
and n means nodes

169
00:20:11,019 --> 00:20:15,019
in a control flow graph.

170
00:20:15,019 --> 00:20:18,759
Second, the same value is written as

171
00:20:18,759 --> 00:20:23,299
V equals to d plus 1,

172
00:20:23,299 --> 00:20:26,299
where d is the number of decision nodes

173
00:20:26,299 --> 00:20:28,299
in the program.

174
00:20:28,299 --> 00:20:32,099
The common assumption is very clear.

175
00:20:32,099 --> 00:20:36,289
When the value of V is high,

176
00:20:36,289 --> 00:20:38,289
the program is seen as

177
00:20:38,289 --> 00:20:41,579
fault-prone and hard to maintain.

178
00:20:41,579 --> 00:20:43,579
Many people directly connect

179
00:20:43,579 --> 00:20:45,579
a high Psylomatic Number

180
00:20:45,579 --> 00:20:47,579
with high complexity.

181
00:20:47,579 --> 00:20:52,579
But the reality is more subtle.

182
00:20:52,579 --> 00:20:55,250
Psylomatic Number is mainly

183
00:20:55,250 --> 00:20:58,250
a count of decisions.

184
00:20:58,250 --> 00:21:02,250
It tells us how many different paths

185
00:21:02,250 --> 00:21:05,920
exist in the code.

186
00:21:05,920 --> 00:21:07,920
A program can contain

187
00:21:07,920 --> 00:21:09,920
many decision points

188
00:21:09,920 --> 00:21:12,920
and still be easy to read

189
00:21:12,920 --> 00:21:14,920
and easy to understand.

190
00:21:14,920 --> 00:21:17,750
And because of this,

191
00:21:17,750 --> 00:21:19,750
we must be careful

192
00:21:19,750 --> 00:21:22,750
with interpretation.

193
00:21:22,750 --> 00:21:31,799
Psylomatic complexity

194
00:21:31,799 --> 00:21:36,140
is a valid measure of decisions,

195
00:21:36,140 --> 00:21:39,210
but it's only a partial measure

196
00:21:39,210 --> 00:21:41,210
of complexity.

197
00:21:41,210 --> 00:21:45,589
It does not capture readability,

198
00:21:45,589 --> 00:21:47,589
structure, naming,

199
00:21:47,589 --> 00:21:49,589
or design quality.

200
00:21:49,589 --> 00:21:54,609
So the key lesson in this,

201
00:21:54,609 --> 00:21:56,609
Psylomatic Number gives

202
00:21:56,609 --> 00:21:58,609
useful information,

203
00:21:58,609 --> 00:22:01,609
but when it is used alone

204
00:22:01,609 --> 00:22:03,609
to represent complexity,

205
00:22:03,609 --> 00:22:06,609
it can be misleading.

206
00:22:06,609 --> 00:22:10,049
Numbers are helpful,

207
00:22:10,049 --> 00:22:13,049
but only when we clearly understand

208
00:22:13,049 --> 00:22:16,049
what they really measure.

209
00:22:16,049 --> 00:22:20,049
We need to be careful about this.

210
00:22:20,049 --> 00:22:29,319
So the next slide,

211
00:22:29,319 --> 00:22:32,319
I think it is

212
00:22:32,319 --> 00:22:35,509
Direct vs. Derived

213
00:22:35,509 --> 00:22:38,180
Measurement.

214
00:22:38,180 --> 00:22:56,309
In this slide,

215
00:22:56,309 --> 00:22:58,789
we focus on the mechanics

216
00:22:58,789 --> 00:23:00,789
of measurements.

217
00:23:00,789 --> 00:23:04,619
Specifically, we compare

218
00:23:04,619 --> 00:23:06,619
direct measurements

219
00:23:06,619 --> 00:23:08,619
and derivative measurements.

220
00:23:08,619 --> 00:23:11,450
First, let's look at

221
00:23:11,450 --> 00:23:13,450
direct measurements.

222
00:23:13,450 --> 00:23:16,799
A direct measurement involves

223
00:23:16,799 --> 00:23:19,799
no other attribute.

224
00:23:19,799 --> 00:23:23,440
We measure one thing directly

225
00:23:23,440 --> 00:23:26,440
without using another value.

226
00:23:26,440 --> 00:23:31,259
The most common example is length.

227
00:23:31,259 --> 00:23:34,549
Measures with a ruler.

228
00:23:34,549 --> 00:23:37,289
In software,

229
00:23:37,289 --> 00:23:40,380
similar direct measurements

230
00:23:40,380 --> 00:23:44,380
are source code size,

231
00:23:44,380 --> 00:23:46,380
LOC,

232
00:23:46,380 --> 00:23:48,380
defect count,

233
00:23:48,380 --> 00:23:50,380
and testing hours.

234
00:23:50,380 --> 00:23:53,380
Each of these values

235
00:23:53,380 --> 00:23:55,380
is observed

236
00:23:55,380 --> 00:23:57,380
and counted directly.

237
00:23:57,380 --> 00:24:01,339
Now, let's look

238
00:24:01,339 --> 00:24:03,559
to the derivative measures

239
00:24:03,559 --> 00:24:05,559
of measurements.

240
00:24:05,559 --> 00:24:07,559
A derivative measurement

241
00:24:07,559 --> 00:24:09,559
is defined in terms

242
00:24:09,559 --> 00:24:12,710
of other attributes.

243
00:24:12,710 --> 00:24:15,710
This means we calculate it

244
00:24:15,710 --> 00:24:18,710
by combining two or more

245
00:24:18,710 --> 00:24:20,710
direct measurements.

246
00:24:20,710 --> 00:24:24,410
The classic example is

247
00:24:24,410 --> 00:24:27,410
density.

248
00:24:27,410 --> 00:24:32,140
It is defined as

249
00:24:32,140 --> 00:24:35,140
mass divided by volume,

250
00:24:35,140 --> 00:24:36,430
as you know.

251
00:24:36,430 --> 00:24:37,430
In software,

252
00:24:37,430 --> 00:24:39,430
we use the same idea.

253
00:24:39,430 --> 00:24:41,720
For example,

254
00:24:41,720 --> 00:24:43,720
programmer productivity

255
00:24:43,720 --> 00:24:44,720
is measured as

256
00:24:44,720 --> 00:24:47,720
LOC per person amount.

257
00:24:47,720 --> 00:24:50,299
Another example is

258
00:24:50,299 --> 00:24:52,299
defect density,

259
00:24:52,299 --> 00:24:54,299
defined as defects divided

260
00:24:54,299 --> 00:24:56,299
by model size.

261
00:24:56,299 --> 00:24:59,059
The key point is shown

262
00:24:59,059 --> 00:25:01,059
in the sentence

263
00:25:01,059 --> 00:25:03,059
at the bottom of this slide.

264
00:25:03,059 --> 00:25:05,670
Derivative measurement

265
00:25:05,670 --> 00:25:07,670
makes visible

266
00:25:07,670 --> 00:25:10,670
the interactions

267
00:25:10,670 --> 00:25:12,670
between attributes.

268
00:25:12,670 --> 00:25:14,670
It helps us understand

269
00:25:14,670 --> 00:25:16,670
relationships,

270
00:25:16,670 --> 00:25:20,740
not just row numbers.

271
00:25:20,740 --> 00:25:23,950
So,

272
00:25:23,950 --> 00:25:25,950
direct measures

273
00:25:25,950 --> 00:25:28,950
tell us what exists,

274
00:25:28,950 --> 00:25:30,950
while derivative measures

275
00:25:30,950 --> 00:25:33,950
help us understand

276
00:25:33,950 --> 00:25:35,950
how things relate

277
00:25:35,950 --> 00:25:37,950
