1050
00:47:54,619 --> 00:48:02,280
As we move to the right, the scale becomes richer and more sophisticated.

1051
00:48:04,119 --> 00:48:08,619
At the same time, the rules become more restrictive.

1052
00:48:10,260 --> 00:48:11,679
Let's start from the left.

1053
00:48:13,260 --> 00:48:15,559
The first scale is nominal.

1054
00:48:17,139 --> 00:48:19,800
Nominal scales are only labels.

1055
00:48:20,239 --> 00:48:25,929
They allow us to say difference or same, but nothing more.

1056
00:48:25,929 --> 00:48:30,690
There is no order and no size.

1057
00:48:34,329 --> 00:48:36,690
Next is the ordinal scale.

1058
00:48:38,500 --> 00:48:41,300
Here we can rank the things.

1059
00:48:42,119 --> 00:48:51,679
We know which one is higher or lower, but we do not know the exact distance between them.

1060
00:48:51,679 --> 00:48:58,699
After that comes the interval scale.

1061
00:49:00,579 --> 00:49:02,719
With interval scales...

1062
00:49:02,840 --> 00:49:04,869
Differences matter.

1063
00:49:05,869 --> 00:49:09,869
The distance between values is meaningful.

1064
00:49:11,130 --> 00:49:15,190
However, there is still no true zero.

1065
00:49:16,190 --> 00:49:19,800
Then we have the ratio scale after that.

1066
00:49:20,800 --> 00:49:22,900
The scale has true zero.

1067
00:49:24,150 --> 00:49:31,409
Because of that, ratios like twice as much are meaningful.

1068
00:49:33,300 --> 00:49:35,300
At the top, we see the difference.

1069
00:49:36,300 --> 00:49:40,090
Absolute scale.

1070
00:49:41,090 --> 00:49:42,090
Absolute scale.

1071
00:49:43,090 --> 00:49:45,090
This is the strongest scale.

1072
00:49:46,090 --> 00:49:52,489
Counting items is a typical example.

1073
00:49:53,489 --> 00:49:59,489
On the right side of the slide, we see an important definition.

1074
00:50:00,869 --> 00:50:04,869
A scale is made of three parts.

1075
00:50:05,869 --> 00:50:07,320
The mapping.

1076
00:50:08,320 --> 00:50:09,320
The empirical system.

1077
00:50:10,739 --> 00:50:11,739
And the numerical system.

1078
00:50:12,739 --> 00:50:18,849
Below that, we see the term admissible transformation.

1079
00:50:19,849 --> 00:50:27,300
This means the rules that allow us to change one measurement in another.

1080
00:50:28,300 --> 00:50:31,300
For example, from inches to centimeters.

1081
00:50:32,300 --> 00:50:34,300
Without losing meaning.

1082
00:50:36,260 --> 00:50:40,260
The key idea here is simple but very important.

1083
00:50:40,260 --> 00:50:47,480
Not every operation is allowed on every scale.

1084
00:50:47,480 --> 00:50:53,480
If we use the wrong scale, our analysis can become meaningless.

1085
00:50:54,579 --> 00:51:02,610
So, before measuring or analyzing data, we must always ask...

1086
00:51:03,610 --> 00:51:12,579
Which measurement scale am I using?

1087
00:51:12,579 --> 00:51:26,420
So, let me go through another slide.

1088
00:51:32,449 --> 00:51:37,449
Numeral scales are used for classification only.

1089
00:51:38,800 --> 00:51:42,800
They separate items into different classes.

1090
00:51:44,570 --> 00:51:53,820
Each class represents a different type, such as specification files, design files, and code files.

1091
00:51:53,820 --> 00:51:58,980
These categories are distinct, but they are not ordered.

1092
00:51:59,980 --> 00:52:04,269
There is no meaning of more or less in nominal scales.

1093
00:52:05,269 --> 00:52:10,269
A design file is not greater than a code file.

1094
00:52:11,909 --> 00:52:14,909
They are simply different kinds.

1095
00:52:16,840 --> 00:52:21,840
The numbers used in nominal scales are labels only.

1096
00:52:21,840 --> 00:52:26,840
They do not represent size, distance, or priority.

1097
00:52:27,840 --> 00:52:32,219
Because of this, numbers can be changed freely.

1098
00:52:33,219 --> 00:52:36,219
As long as each label stays unique.

1099
00:52:37,219 --> 00:52:44,960
For example, one category can be mapped from 1 to 101.

1100
00:52:45,989 --> 00:52:49,989
Another from 2 to 69.

1101
00:52:49,989 --> 00:52:55,440
And another from 3 to 73.

1102
00:52:57,300 --> 00:53:04,300
This kind of change is allowed because it is a one-to-one transformation.

1103
00:53:05,880 --> 00:53:07,880
The key idea is here.

1104
00:53:08,880 --> 00:53:09,880
It is simple.

1105
00:53:10,940 --> 00:53:16,940
Nominal scales answer the question...

1106
00:53:18,420 --> 00:53:21,420
Are these the same or different?

1107
00:53:21,420 --> 00:53:27,650
They do not answer which is better or which is larger.

1108
00:53:28,840 --> 00:53:33,840
Only it asks are these the same or different.

1109
00:53:42,869 --> 00:53:43,869
Maybe...

1110
00:53:44,869 --> 00:53:46,869
No, it's not the last slide.

1111
00:53:48,159 --> 00:53:50,159
Only we have two or more, maybe.

1112
00:53:53,300 --> 00:53:59,739
Oops.

1113
00:53:59,739 --> 00:54:00,739
Yes.

1114
00:54:03,820 --> 00:54:06,820
Ordinal scales are used for ranking.

1115
00:54:06,820 --> 00:54:15,969
They make nominal categories and add order to them.

1116
00:54:16,969 --> 00:54:21,000
A common example is severity levels.

1117
00:54:22,610 --> 00:54:30,659
Low severity comes before medium severity.

1118
00:54:31,659 --> 00:54:32,659
Yes.

1119
00:54:33,659 --> 00:54:35,659
It comes before medium severity.

1120
00:54:35,659 --> 00:54:40,730
A medium severity comes before high severity.

1121
00:54:41,949 --> 00:54:43,949
This ordering is meaningful.

1122
00:54:47,230 --> 00:54:50,230
High severity is worse than medium severity.

1123
00:54:51,230 --> 00:54:54,230
And medium severity is worse than low severity.

1124
00:54:55,550 --> 00:54:58,550
However, the size of the difference is unknown.

1125
00:54:59,550 --> 00:55:06,900
It's possible to say that high severity is twice as bad as medium severity.

1126
00:55:06,900 --> 00:55:11,900
Because of this, arithmetic operations have no meaning.

1127
00:55:12,900 --> 00:55:15,900
Addition and subtraction do not make sense here.

1128
00:55:16,900 --> 00:55:25,329
Only the order matters, not the distance between levels.

1129
00:55:26,329 --> 00:55:32,579
The allowed transformation must preserve the order.

1130
00:55:34,000 --> 00:55:39,000
Numbers can change, but the ranking must stay the same.

1131
00:55:39,000 --> 00:55:45,900
The key question answered by ordinal scales is quite simple.

1132
00:55:47,539 --> 00:55:52,539
Which comes before and which comes after?

1133
00:55:54,019 --> 00:55:57,019
They do not answer how much worse.

1134
